{"title_page": "Wabeeneeye", "text_new": "{{About|the sub clan of Majeerteen|the geographical area|Somalia}}\n{{notability|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group|\n|group= Wabeeneeye \n|image=\n|poptime=\n|region1 = {{flagcountry|Somalia}}\n|region2 = {{flagcountry|Yemen}}\n|region3 = {{flagcountry|Ethiopia}}\n|region4 = {{flagcountry|Kenya}}\n|langs   = [[Somali language|Somali]] \n|rels    = [[Islam]]\n|related-c = [[Dishiishe]], [[Dhulbahante]], [[Warsangali]], [[Marehan]], [[Ogaden]] and other [[Darod]] clans. \n}}\n\n'''Wabeeneeye''' ({{lang-so|Wabeeneeye}}, {{lang-ar|\u0648\u0627\u0628\u064a\u0646\u0627\u064a\u064a}}) is a sub clan of the [[Majeerteen]] clan family and within the larger [[Harti]] clan and thereafter in the [[Darod clan|Darod]]. Its members inhabit the western and northern portions of [[Bari, Somalia|Bari]] in Somalia, primarily found in and around [[Bandar Ziyada|Qaw]] and [[Bosaso]]. They also inhabit communities in [[Nugal, Somalia|Nugal]] and [[Mudug]] area, There is a significant Wabeeneeye community in the port city [[Kismayo]] and they have expat communities doing business in [[Nairobi]], [[Mombasa]], [[Kampala]], [[Dubai]], [[Durban]] and [[Yemen]].\n\n==Overview==\nThe '''Wabeneeye''' clan trace their lineage to the eldest son of [[Majeerteen|Muhammad Harti Amaleh Abdi Muhammad Abdirahman Jaberti(Majeerteen)]]. \u2018Wabeneeye\u2019, a nickname bestowed on him by his peers for his exceptionally straightforward and honest nature. It is a phonetic corruption of \u2018ma beneeye\u2019 literally translating to \u2018does not lie\u2019.\n\nWabeeneeye had two sons:\n*Ali Wabeeneeye Muhammad\n*Ahmed Wabeeneeye Muhammad\n\n==History==\nThe '''Wabeeneeye''' clan are known as a mercantile and industrious people with an established and extensive history in local and international trade. Historically known for exporting livestock, dry-fish, animal-skin, myrrh and frankincense, they remain one of the larger exporters in various industries. In past centuries they were among the primary importers of various goods such as foods, beverages, medicines, clothes, fishing gears and other important commodities from Persian Gulf, India, and Zanzibar. Most of the trade occurred through the port in Bandar Siyaada, commonly known as [[Bandar Ziyada|Qaw]].\n\nTheir historical trade hub was the port town of Bander Siyada also known as Qaw. Ultimately destroyed and abandoned by the British colonials when the colonial divided the Somali territory into five parts <ref>http://www.togdheer.com/history/introduction.shtml</ref>. It lays on the border between British Somaliland and (former) Italian Somaliland. There has been extensive interest and efforts in re-building and improving the town by the Wabeeneeye subclan, primary from the neighboring cities as well as the diaspora.\n\n==Lineage==\nThere is no clear agreement on the clan and sub-clan structures and many lineages are omitted. The following listing is taken from the [[World Bank]]'s ''Conflict in Somalia: Drivers and Dynamics'' from 2005 and the [[United Kingdom]]'s [[Home Office]] publication, ''Somalia Assessment 2001''.<ref name=\"worldbank55\">Worldbank, ''[http://siteresources.worldbank.org/INTSOMALIA/Resources/conflictinsomalia.pdf Conflict in Somalia: Drivers and Dynamics] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616164535/http://siteresources.worldbank.org/INTSOMALIA/Resources/conflictinsomalia.pdf |date=2018-06-16 }}'', January 2005, Appendix 2, Lineage Charts, p.55 Figure A-1</ref><ref name=\"ind01b_somalia_ca\">[http://www.asylumlaw.org/docs/somalia/ind01b_somalia_ca.pdf Country Information and Policy Unit, Home Office, Great Britain, Somalia Assessment 2001, Annex B: Somali Clan Structure] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716081350/http://www.asylumlaw.org/docs/somalia/ind01b_somalia_ca.pdf |date=2011-07-16 }}, p. 43</ref>\n\n* Shiekh [[Darod]] (Daarood bin Ismaciil)\n** Marehan\n*** Red Dini\n*** Rer Hassan\n*** Cali Dheere\n** Kabalah\n*** Absame\n**** Ogaden\n***** Makabul\n***** Mohamed Zubeir\n***** Aulihan\n**** Jidwaq\n*** Harti\n**** [[Dhulbahante]]\n**** [[Dishiishe]]\n**** [[Warsangali]]\n**** '''[[Majeerteen]]'''\n*****'''Wabeeneeye'''(Muhammud Majeerteen)\n******Ali Wabeeneeye\n******Ahmed Wabeeneeye\n*******Idris Ahmed\n*******Dhuub Ahmed\n*******Caraale Ahmed\n*****Aawe\n******Idigfale (Muuse Noleys)\n******Danweyne (Abdalle Noleys)\n******Amaanle\n******Guddoonwaaq\n******Filkucaag\n******Amartiwaaq (allamagan xajiijle)\n******Tabale\n******Ali Jibraahiil\n******Nuux Jibrahiil\n******Cabdirixiin Ibraahim\n******Wadalmoge\n******Reer Umar\n******Reer Maxamuud\n*******Abukar Maxamuud\n********Faarax Ismacil\n********Ciise Ismacil\n********Maxamed Ismacil\n*******Qaasin Maxamuud\n********Maxamed Qaasin\n********Axmed Qaasin\n********Aadan Qaasin\n********Bare Qaasin\n********Ibraahim Qaasin\n******Reer Bicidyahan\n******Siwaaqroon\n*******Abdirahman\n********Adan Abdiraxman\n*********Ibrahim Abdisamad\n*********Yoonis Abdisamad\n*********Liibaan Abdisamad\n*********Mohamud Abdisamad\n********Cawlyahan (Obokor Abdiraxman)\n*********Ciise Cawlyahan\n*********Jibriil Cawlyahan\n*********Hashim Cawlyahan\n*********Yuusuf Cawlyahan\n*******Mohammed\n*********Gahayle\n*********Dhaadaar\n*******Odayma'arke\n******Ugaar Saleebaan\n******Ismail Saleebaan\n******Ali Saleebaan\n*******Bicidyahan Ali\n*******Auliyahan Ali\n*******Omar Ali\n*******Adam Ali\n*******Ismail Ali\n******Maxamuud Saleebaan\n*******Cumar Maxamuud\n*******Cusmaan Maxamuud\n*******Ciise Maxamuud\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120206024446/http://www.mudugonline.com/MajertainSaltanates/Sultanate.htm The Majeerteen Sultanates]\n\n{{Somali clans}}\n\n[[Category:Somali clans in Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:Somali clans]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the sub clan of Majeerteen|the geographical area|Somalia}}\n{{notability|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox ethnic group|\n|group= Wabeeneeye \n|image=\n|poptime=\n|region1 = {{flagcountry|Somalia}}\n|region2 = {{flagcountry|Yemen}}\n|region3 = {{flagcountry|Ethiopia}}\n|region4 = {{flagcountry|Kenya}}\n|langs   = [[Somali language|Somali]] \n|rels    = [[Islam]]\n|related-c = [[Dishiishe]], [[Dhulbahante]], [[Warsangali]], [[Marehan]], [[Ogaden]] and other [[Darod]] clans. \n}}\n\n'''Wabeeneeye''' ({{lang-so|Wabeeneeye}}, {{lang-ar|\u0648\u0627\u0628\u064a\u0646\u0627\u064a\u064a}}) is a sub clan of the [[Majeerteen]] clan family and within the larger [[Harti]] clan and thereafter in the [[Darod clan|Darod]]. Its members inhabit the western and northern portions of [[Bari, Somalia|Bari]] in Somalia, primarily found in and around [[Bandar Ziyada|Qaw]] and [[Bosaso]]. They also inhabit communities in [[Nugal, Somalia|Nugal]] and [[Mudug]] area, There is a significant Wabeeneeye community in the port city [[Kismayo]] and they have expat communities doing business in [[Nairobi]], [[Mombasa]], [[Kampala]], [[Dubai]], [[Durban]] and [[Yemen]].\n\n==Overview==\nThe '''Wabeneeye''' clan trace their lineage to the eldest son of [[Majeerteen|Muhammad Harti Amaleh Abdi Muhammad Abdirahman Jaberti(Majeerteen)]]. \u2018Wabeneeye\u2019, a nickname bestowed on him by his peers for his exceptionally straightforward and honest nature. It is a phonetic corruption of \u2018ma beneeye\u2019 literally translating to \u2018does not lie\u2019.\n\nWabeeneeye had two sons:\n*Ali Wabeeneeye Muhammad\n*Ahmed Wabeeneeye Muhammad\n\n==History==\nThe '''Wabeeneeye''' clan are known as a mercantile and industrious people with an established and extensive history in local and international trade. Historically known for exporting livestock, dry-fish, animal-skin, myrrh and frankincense, they remain one of the larger exporters in various industries. In past centuries they were among the primary importers of various goods such as foods, beverages, medicines, clothes, fishing gears and other important commodities from Persian Gulf, India, and Zanzibar. Most of the trade occurred through the port in Bandar Siyaada, commonly known as [[Bandar Ziyada|Qaw]].\n\nTheir historical trade hub was the port town of Bander Siyada. Ultimately destroyed and abandoned by the British colonials when the colonial divided the Somali territory into five parts <ref>http://www.togdheer.com/history/introduction.shtml</ref>. It lays on the border between British Somaliland and (former) Italian Somaliland. There has been extensive interest and efforts in re-building and improving the town by the Wabeeneeye subclan, primary from the neighboring cities as well as the diaspora.\n\n==Lineage==\nThere is no clear agreement on the clan and sub-clan structures and many lineages are omitted. The following listing is taken from the [[World Bank]]'s ''Conflict in Somalia: Drivers and Dynamics'' from 2005 and the [[United Kingdom]]'s [[Home Office]] publication, ''Somalia Assessment 2001''.<ref name=\"worldbank55\">Worldbank, ''[http://siteresources.worldbank.org/INTSOMALIA/Resources/conflictinsomalia.pdf Conflict in Somalia: Drivers and Dynamics] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616164535/http://siteresources.worldbank.org/INTSOMALIA/Resources/conflictinsomalia.pdf |date=2018-06-16 }}'', January 2005, Appendix 2, Lineage Charts, p.55 Figure A-1</ref><ref name=\"ind01b_somalia_ca\">[http://www.asylumlaw.org/docs/somalia/ind01b_somalia_ca.pdf Country Information and Policy Unit, Home Office, Great Britain, Somalia Assessment 2001, Annex B: Somali Clan Structure] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716081350/http://www.asylumlaw.org/docs/somalia/ind01b_somalia_ca.pdf |date=2011-07-16 }}, p. 43</ref>\n\n* Shiekh [[Darod]] (Daarood bin Ismaciil)\n** Marehan\n*** Red Dini\n*** Rer Hassan\n*** Cali Dheere\n** Kabalah\n*** Absame\n**** Ogaden\n***** Makabul\n***** Mohamed Zubeir\n***** Aulihan\n**** Jidwaq\n*** Harti\n**** [[Dhulbahante]]\n**** [[Dishiishe]]\n**** [[Warsangali]]\n**** '''[[Majeerteen]]'''\n*****'''Wabeeneeye'''(Muhammud Majeerteen)\n******Ali Wabeeneeye\n******Ahmed Wabeeneeye\n*******Idris Ahmed\n*******Dhuub Ahmed\n*******Caraale Ahmed\n*****Aawe\n******Idigfale (Muuse Noleys)\n******Danweyne (Abdalle Noleys)\n******Amaanle\n******Guddoonwaaq\n******Filkucaag\n******Amartiwaaq (allamagan xajiijle)\n******Tabale\n******Ali Jibraahiil\n******Nuux Jibrahiil\n******Cabdirixiin Ibraahim\n******Wadalmoge\n******Reer Umar\n******Reer Maxamuud\n*******Abukar Maxamuud\n********Faarax Ismacil\n********Ciise Ismacil\n********Maxamed Ismacil\n*******Qaasin Maxamuud\n********Maxamed Qaasin\n********Axmed Qaasin\n********Aadan Qaasin\n********Bare Qaasin\n********Ibraahim Qaasin\n******Reer Bicidyahan\n******Siwaaqroon\n*******Abdirahman\n********Adan Abdiraxman\n*********Ibrahim Abdisamad\n*********Yoonis Abdisamad\n*********Liibaan Abdisamad\n*********Mohamud Abdisamad\n********Cawlyahan (Obokor Abdiraxman)\n*********Ciise Cawlyahan\n*********Jibriil Cawlyahan\n*********Hashim Cawlyahan\n*********Yuusuf Cawlyahan\n*******Mohammed\n*********Gahayle\n*********Dhaadaar\n*******Odayma'arke\n******Ugaar Saleebaan\n******Ismail Saleebaan\n******Ali Saleebaan\n*******Bicidyahan Ali\n*******Auliyahan Ali\n*******Omar Ali\n*******Adam Ali\n*******Ismail Ali\n******Maxamuud Saleebaan\n*******Cumar Maxamuud\n*******Cusmaan Maxamuud\n*******Ciise Maxamuud\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120206024446/http://www.mudugonline.com/MajertainSaltanates/Sultanate.htm The Majeerteen Sultanates]\n\n{{Somali clans}}\n\n[[Category:Somali clans in Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:Somali clans]]\n", "name_user": "Ducaysane911", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eHistory)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wabeeneeye"}
{"title_page": "Hiraab", "text_new": "{{Infobox ethnic group|\n|group=Hiraab\n|image=\n|poptime= \n|region1 = {{flagcountry|Somalia}} \n|langs=[[Somali language|Somali]]   \n|region2 = {{flagcountry|Ethiopia}}\n|region3 = {{flagcountry|Kenya}}\n|region4 = {{flagcountry|Yemen}}\n|rels = [[Islam]] ([[Sunni Islam|Sunni]], [[Sufism]])\n|related-c= [[Dir (clan)|Dir]], [[Darod]], [[Isaaq]], other [[Somali clan]]s<!-- CONFIRMED RELATIONS!!! -->\n}}\n\n'''Hiraab''' is a [[Somali clan]], and one of the  Gorgarte [[Hawiye]] subclans. Hiraab members live in central and southern [[Somalia]], from [[Galkayo]] and  [[Kismayo]]. Most of them, such as the [[Abgaal]], live in [[Mogadishu]]. Others live in the [[Somali Region]] of [[Ethiopia]]. They once formed a kingdom which successfully revolted against the [[Ajuran Sultanate]] and established an independent Hiraab Imamate, which included [[Hobyo]].<ref name=\"Lee V. Cassanelli 1982\">Lee V. Cassanelli, The shaping of Somali society., Philadelphia, 1982,</ref> According to [[Bernhard Helander|Dr. Bernhard Helander]] of [[Uppsala University]], \"the Imam of Hiraab is a hereditary position that traditionally is held by a person of the \nfirst-born branch, the Mudulod.\"<ref>{{cite web |first=Helander |last=Bernhard |title=The Hiraab Treaty |url=http://www.etext.org/Politics/Somalia.News.Update/Volume.3/snu-03.003 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070224161113/http://www.etext.org/Politics/Somalia.News.Update/Volume.3/snu-03.003 |work=Somalia News Update |publisher=Dr. Bernhard Helander, [[Uppsala University]] |location=[[Uppsala]], [[Sweden]] |date=1994-01-19 |archivedate=2007-02-24 |accessdate=2009-03-31 |quote=The Imam of Hiraab is a hereditary position that traditionally is held by a person of the  first-born branch, the Mudulod. }}</ref>\n\n==Hiraab sub-clans==\n[[Ali Jimale Ahmed]] outlines the Hiraab clan genealogical tree in ''The Invention of Somalia'':<ref name=\"ali_jimale_ahmed\">{{Cite book | author=[[Ali Jimale Ahmed]] | title=The Invention of Somalia | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XpdAzRYruCwC&lpg=PA129&dq=Mudulood&pg=PA123#v=onepage&q&f=false | page=123 | year=1995 | publisher=Red Sea | location=[[Lawrenceville, New Jersey|Lawrenceville]], [[New Jersey|NJ]] | isbn=0-932415-98-9}}</ref>\n* [[Hawiye]]\n** Goorgarte\n*** '''Hiraab'''\n**** Mudulood \n***** Abgaal\n***** Hilibi Daarandoole\n***** Wacdaan\n***** Moobleen\n***** Ujejeen\n**** Duduble(Maxamud hirab)\n**** Dudub (Maxamed hirab)\n**** [[Habar Gidir|Habarghidir]]\n***** Sacad\n***** Saleebaan\n***** [[Ayr (clan)|Cayr]]\n***** Saruur\n**** [[Sheekhaal]]\n* Looboge\n* Qudub\n* Gandarshe\n* Ree Awxasan.\n* Guudlaawe\n* Jaziira\n* Qaaluu\n<ref>Richard Burton, ''First Footsteps in East Africa'', 1856; edited with an introduction and additional chapters by Gordon Waterfield (New York: Praeger, 1966), p. 165</ref> <ref>https://www.ecoi.net/file_upload/90_1261130976_accord-report-clans-in-somalia-revised-edition-20091215.pdf Clans in Somalia Report on a Lecture by Joakim Gundel, COI Workshop Vienna, 15 May 2009 (Revised Edition) published December 2009</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Refbegin}}\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Refend}}\n{{clear}}\n\n{{Somali clans}}\n\n[[Category:Hawiye clan]]\n[[Category:Somali clans in Ethiopia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox ethnic group|\n|group=Hiraab\n|image=\n|poptime= \n|region1 = {{flagcountry|Somalia}} \n|langs=[[Somali language|Somali]]   \n|region2 = {{flagcountry|Ethiopia}}\n|region3 = {{flagcountry|Kenya}}\n|region4 = {{flagcountry|Yemen}}\n|rels = [[Islam]] ([[Sunni Islam|Sunni]], [[Sufism]])\n|related-c= [[Dir (clan)|Dir]], [[Darod]], [[Isaaq]], other [[Somali clan]]s<!-- CONFIRMED RELATIONS!!! -->\n}}\n\n'''Hiraab''' is a [[Somali clan]], and one of the  Gorgarte [[Hawiye]] subclans. Hiraab members live in central and southern [[Somalia]], from [[Galkayo]] and shiikhaal [[Kismayo]]. Most of them, such as the [[Abgaal]], live in [[Mogadishu]]. Others live in the [[Somali Region]] of [[Ethiopia]]. They once formed a kingdom which successfully revolted against the [[Ajuran Sultanate]] and established an independent Hiraab Imamate, which included [[Hobyo]].<ref name=\"Lee V. Cassanelli 1982\">Lee V. Cassanelli, The shaping of Somali society., Philadelphia, 1982,</ref> According to [[Bernhard Helander|Dr. Bernhard Helander]] of [[Uppsala University]], \"the Imam of Hiraab is a hereditary position that traditionally is held by a person of the \nfirst-born branch, the Mudulod.\"<ref>{{cite web |first=Helander |last=Bernhard |title=The Hiraab Treaty |url=http://www.etext.org/Politics/Somalia.News.Update/Volume.3/snu-03.003 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070224161113/http://www.etext.org/Politics/Somalia.News.Update/Volume.3/snu-03.003 |work=Somalia News Update |publisher=Dr. Bernhard Helander, [[Uppsala University]] |location=[[Uppsala]], [[Sweden]] |date=1994-01-19 |archivedate=2007-02-24 |accessdate=2009-03-31 |quote=The Imam of Hiraab is a hereditary position that traditionally is held by a person of the  first-born branch, the Mudulod. }}</ref>\n\n==Hiraab sub-clans==\n[[Ali Jimale Ahmed]] outlines the Hiraab clan genealogical tree in ''The Invention of Somalia'':<ref name=\"ali_jimale_ahmed\">{{Cite book | author=[[Ali Jimale Ahmed]] | title=The Invention of Somalia | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XpdAzRYruCwC&lpg=PA129&dq=Mudulood&pg=PA123#v=onepage&q&f=false | page=123 | year=1995 | publisher=Red Sea | location=[[Lawrenceville, New Jersey|Lawrenceville]], [[New Jersey|NJ]] | isbn=0-932415-98-9}}</ref>\n* [[Hawiye]]\n** Goorgarte\n*** '''Hiraab'''\n**** Mudulood \n***** Abgaal\n***** Hilibi Daarandoole\n***** Wacdaan\n***** Moobleen\n***** Ujejeen\n**** Duduble(Maxamud hirab)\n**** Dudub (Maxamed hirab)\n**** [[Habar Gidir|Habarghidir]]\n***** Sacad\n***** Saleebaan\n***** [[Ayr (clan)|Cayr]]\n***** Saruur\n**** [[Sheekhaal]]\n* Looboge\n* Qudub\n* Gandarshe\n* Ree Awxasan.\n* Guudlaawe\n* Jaziira\n* Qaaluu\n<ref>Richard Burton, ''