{"title_page": "Helmut Winschermann", "text_new": "{{infobox musician\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1920|3|22}}\n|birth_place = [[M\u00fclheim]], [[Germany]]\n|background = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n|occupation = Conductor, musician, teacher\n|instrument = Oboe\n|associated_acts = Municipal Orchestra of Oberhausen<br>[[Deutsche Bachsolisten]]\n}}\n'''Helmut Winschermann''' (born 22 March 1920) is a German classical oboist, conductor and teacher.  He founded the [[Deutsche Bachsolisten]] (German Bach Soloists) and has been their conductor since 1960.\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Deutsche Bachsolisten 1973 on tour of Southern Africa.jpeg|thumb|right|Photo 1973, Bachsolisten orchestra tour Southern Adrica.Dedicated to tour organiser Hans Adler.[http://classicalmusicianstoza.blogspot.ca/2014/06/deutche-bachsolisten-under-helmut.html] \u2248]] -->\n\n==Career==\nHelmut Winschermann was born in [[M\u00fclheim|M\u00fclheim an der Ruhr]] in 1920.  He became an orchestral oboist with the Municipal Orchestra of [[Oberhausen]] after studying in Essen and Paris.  From 1945 he was principal oboe with the [[hr-Sinfonieorchester|Frankfurt Radio Symphony Orchestra]] including in its period known as the Hessen Radio Symphony Orchestra.<ref name=all>[http://www.allmusic.com/artist/helmut-winschermann-mn0000574882/biography AllMusic]; Retrieved 27 August 2013</ref>\n\nWith the flautist [[Kurt Redel]] and harpsichordist Irmgard Lechner, he was a co-founder of the chamber music ensemble Collegium Pro Arte, later called the Collegium Instrumentale Detmold.\n\nIn 1956 he was appointed principal chair of the oboe department at the [[Hochschule f\u00fcr Musik Detmold]], having taught there since 1948.<ref name=all/>  His students include [[Hansj\u00f6rg Schellenberger]], [[Fumiaki Miyamoto]], [[Ingo Goritzki]], G\u00fcnther Passin and Gernot Schmalfu\u00df.\n\nHe recorded the [[Oboe Quartet (Mozart)|Mozart Oboe Quartet in F Major (K.370)]] with the [[G\u00fcnter Kehr|Kehr]] Trio issued in 1957 on [[Teldec|Telefunken]] LGX 66065 in the UK.\n\nHe maintained a touring schedule as a soloist, and frequently collaborated with the [[Cappella Coloniensis]], the Chamber Orchestra of the Saar under [[Karl Ristenpart]], and the [[Stuttgart Chamber Orchestra]] under [[Karl M\u00fcnchinger]].\n\nWinschermann founded the instrumental ensemble [[Deutsche Bachsolisten]] in 1960, in order to provide [[historically informed performance]]s of the music of [[Johann Sebastian Bach]] and his baroque contemporaries.  He initially divided his time between playing the oboe and conducting the group, but later focussed on conducting solely.<ref name=all/>  Under his direction they have made a multitude of recordings and toured widely internationally.  They are particularly popular in Japan, having visited there at least 14 times.<ref name=all/>\n\nIn 2010 the group celebrated its 50th anniversary in a concert at the [[Beethovenhalle]] in [[Bonn]], with the 90-year-old Winschermann conducting his own orchestration of Bach's ''[[Goldberg Variations]]''. He [[centenarian|turned 100]] in March 2020.<ref>[https://www.waz.de/staedte/muelheim/muelheims-grosser-oboist-helmut-winschermann-wird-100-jahre-id228748179.html M\u00fclheims gro\u00dfer Oboist Helmut Winschermann ist 100 Jahre alt]</ref>\n\n==Honours==\nIn 1992 Helmut Winschermann was made an Honorary Member of the [[Royal Academy of Music]] in London.<ref name=all/>\n\nIn 2013 he won the [[Georg Philipp Telemann Prize]] of [[Magdeburg]]. He has twice been awarded the [[Edison Prize]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{DNB portal|104011599}}\n* [http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Bio/Winschermann-Helmut.htm Helmut Winschermann (Conductor, Oboe)] bach-cantatas\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Winschermann, Helmut}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:German classical oboists]]\n[[Category:Male oboists]]\n[[Category:German conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:German male conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:Honorary Members of the Royal Academy of Music]]\n[[Category:Historically informed performance]]\n[[Category:Hochschule f\u00fcr Musik Detmold faculty]]\n[[Category:21st-century conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:21st-century German male musicians]]\n[[Category:Officers Crosses of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n[[Category:German centenarians]]\n", "text_old": "{{infobox musician\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1920|3|22}}\n|birth_place = [[M\u00fclheim]], [[Germany]]\n|background = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n|occupation = Conductor, musician, teacher\n|instrument = Oboe\n|associated_acts = Municipal Orchestra of Oberhausen<br>[[Deutsche Bachsolisten]]\n}}\n'''Helmut Winschermann''' (born 22 March 1920) is a German classical oboist, conductor and teacher.  He founded the [[Deutsche Bachsolisten]] (German Bach Soloists) and has been their conductor since 1960.\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Deutsche Bachsolisten 1973 on tour of Southern Africa.jpeg|thumb|right|Photo 1973, Bachsolisten orchestra tour Southern Adrica.Dedicated to tour organiser Hans Adler.[http://classicalmusicianstoza.blogspot.ca/2014/06/deutche-bachsolisten-under-helmut.html] \u2248]] -->\n\n==Career==\nHelmut Winschermann was born in [[M\u00fclheim|M\u00fclheim an der Ruhr]] in 1920.  He became an orchestral oboist with the Municipal Orchestra of [[Oberhausen]] after studying in Essen and Paris.  From 1945 he was principal oboe with the [[hr-Sinfonieorchester|Frankfurt Radio Symphony Orchestra]] including in its period known as the Hessen Radio Symphony Orchestra.<ref name=all>[http://www.allmusic.com/artist/helmut-winschermann-mn0000574882/biography AllMusic]; Retrieved 27 August 2013</ref>\n\nWith the flautist [[Kurt Redel]] and harpsichordist Irmgard Winschermann Lechner, he was a co-founder of the chamber music ensemble Collegium Pro Arte, later called the Collegium Instrumentale Detmold.\n\nIn 1956 he was appointed principal chair of the oboe department at the [[Hochschule f\u00fcr Musik Detmold]], having taught there since 1948.<ref name=all/>  His students include [[Hansj\u00f6rg Schellenberger]], [[Fumiaki Miyamoto]], [[Ingo Goritzki]], G\u00fcnther Passin and Gernot Schmalfu\u00df.\n\nHe recorded the [[Oboe Quartet (Mozart)|Mozart Oboe Quartet in F Major (K.370)]] with the [[G\u00fcnter Kehr|Kehr]] Trio issued in 1957 on [[Teldec|Telefunken]] LGX 66065 in the UK.\n\nHe maintained a touring schedule as a soloist, and frequently collaborated with the [[Cappella Coloniensis]], the Chamber Orchestra of the Saar under [[Karl Ristenpart]], and the [[Stuttgart Chamber Orchestra]] under [[Karl M\u00fcnchinger]].\n\nWinschermann founded the instrumental ensemble [[Deutsche Bachsolisten]] in 1960, in order to provide [[historically informed performance]]s of the music of [[Johann Sebastian Bach]] and his baroque contemporaries.  He initially divided his time between playing the oboe and conducting the group, but later focussed on conducting solely.<ref name=all/>  Under his direction they have made a multitude of recordings and toured widely internationally.  They are particularly popular in Japan, having visited there at least 14 times.<ref name=all/>\n\nIn 2010 the group celebrated its 50th anniversary in a concert at the [[Beethovenhalle]] in [[Bonn]], with the 90-year-old Winschermann conducting his own orchestration of Bach's ''[[Goldberg Variations]]''. He [[centenarian|turned 100]] in March 2020.<ref>[https://www.waz.de/staedte/muelheim/muelheims-grosser-oboist-helmut-winschermann-wird-100-jahre-id228748179.html M\u00fclheims gro\u00dfer Oboist Helmut Winschermann ist 100 Jahre alt]</ref>\n\n==Honours==\nIn 1992 Helmut Winschermann was made an Honorary Member of the [[Royal Academy of Music]] in London.<ref name=all/>\n\nIn 2013 he won the [[Georg Philipp Telemann Prize]] of [[Magdeburg]]. He has twice been awarded the [[Edison Prize]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{DNB portal|104011599}}\n* [http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Bio/Winschermann-Helmut.htm Helmut Winschermann (Conductor, Oboe)] bach-cantatas\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Winschermann, Helmut}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:German classical oboists]]\n[[Category:Male oboists]]\n[[Category:German conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:German male conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:Honorary Members of the Royal Academy of Music]]\n[[Category:Historically informed performance]]\n[[Category:Hochschule f\u00fcr Musik Detmold faculty]]\n[[Category:21st-century conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:21st-century German male musicians]]\n[[Category:Officers Crosses of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n[[Category:German centenarians]]\n", "name_user": "WillisBodine", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removed incorrect \"Winschermann\" from name of Irmgard Lechner, his harpsichordist and colleague in Detmold.  See correct German original.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Helmut_Winschermann"}
{"title_page": "1964 Danish 1st Division", "text_new": "{{Infobox football league season\n| competition        = Danish 1st Division\n| season             = 1964\n| dates              = {{nowrap|26 March \u2013 15 November 1964}}\n| matches            = 132\n| total goals        = 484\n| league topscorer   = [[J\u00f8rgen Ravn]] (21 goals)<ref name=\"pedfod\" />\n| biggest home win   = {{nowrap|[[Aarhus Gymnastikforening|Aarhus GF]] 7\u20131 [[Br\u00f8nsh\u00f8j Boldklub|Br\u00f8nsh\u00f8j BK]]}}<br />(7 June 1964)<ref name=\"has-1d1964\" />\n| biggest away win   = {{nowrap|Br\u00f8nsh\u00f8j BK 0\u20136 [[Akademisk Boldklub|Akademisk BK]]}}<br />(18 October 1964)<ref name=\"has-1d1964\" />\n| highest scoring    = {{nowrap|[[Boldklubben 1909|B 1909]] 6\u20132 [[Kj\u00f8benhavns Boldklub|Kj\u00f8benhavns BK]]}}<br />(5 April 1964)<ref name=\"has-1d1964\" /><br />{{nowrap|Aarhus GF 7\u20131 Br\u00f8nsh\u00f8j BK}}<br />(7 June 1964)<ref name=\"has-1d1964\" /><br />{{nowrap|Kj\u00f8benhavns BK 5\u20133 [[Nyk\u00f8bing Falster Boldklub af 1901|B 1901]]}}<br />(4 October 1964)<ref name=\"has-1d1964\" />\n| winners            = {{nowrap|[[Boldklubben 1909|B 1909]] (2nd title)}}\n| promoted           = \n| relegated          = [[Akademisk Boldklub|Akademisk BK]]<br />[[Br\u00f8nsh\u00f8j Boldklub|Br\u00f8nsh\u00f8j BK]]\n| prevseason         = [[1963 Danish 1st Division|1963]]\n| nextseason         = [[1965 Danish 1st Division|1965]]\n| highest attendance = 43,400<br />{{nowrap|Kj\u00f8benhavns BK 0\u20131 B 1909}}<br />(15 November 1964)<ref name=\"ber-storm\" />\n| attendance         = 554,691<ref name=\"df-dt1964\" />\n| average attendance = 4,202<ref name=\"df-dt1964\" /><!--This is counted manually. 554,691/132=4,202.2045454, rounded.-->\n}}\n\nThe '''1964 Danish 1st Division''' ([[Danish language|Danish]]: '''Danmarksturneringens 1. division 1964''') was the 37th season of Denmark's top-flight association football division since the establishment of Danmarksturneringen's [[Danish football league system|nation-wide league structure]] in 1927, and the 51st edition of the overall [[List of Danish football champions|Danish national football championship]] since its inception in 1912. Governed by the [[Danish Football Association|Danish FA]], the season was launched on 26 March 1964 with a clash between last season's third-placed [[Boldklubben 1903|B 1903]] and [[\u00d8sterbro]]-based and local rivals [[Boldklubben af 1893|B.93]] with the last round of six matches concluding on 15 November 1964.<ref name=\"has-1d1964\" /> [[Esbjerg fB]] were the defending league champions, having won their third consecutive league title [[1963 Danish 1st Division|last season]], while [[Boldklubben Frem|BK Frem]] and [[Boldklubben af 1893|B.93]] entered as promoted teams from the [[1963 Danish 2nd Division]]. Fixtures for the 1964 season were announced in January 1964.\n\nThe club leading the league table after the spring season's first eleven matches were awarded a berth to the [[1964\u201365 European Cup#Preliminary round|1964\u201365 European Cup preliminary round]], while the winners of the [[1963\u201364 Danish Cup]] would quality for the first round of the [[1964\u201365 European Cup Winners' Cup]] \u2014 in case, it turned out to be the same team, the runners-up of the [[1964 Danish Cup Final]] would instead quality for the European Cup Winners' Cup tournament. The overall league winners of 1964 qualified for the [[1965\u201366 European Cup#Preliminary round|1965\u201366 European Cup preliminary round]].<ref name=\"pedfod\" /> The Danish representative in the [[1965\u201366 Inter-Cities Fairs Cup#Second round|1965\u201366 Inter-Cities Fairs Cup second round]] became [[Boldklubben 1903|B 1903]].<ref name=\"pedfod\" />\n\n[[Boldklubben 1909|B 1909]] won the league, secured their second [[List of Danish football champions|Danish league championship]] on the final matchday in front of a record high attendance of 43,400 spectators at [[K\u00f8benhavns Idr\u00e6tspark]], the highest at a Danish league match in history, with [[Aarhus Gymnastikforening|Aarhus GF]] becoming the runners-up for the fourth time in the history.<ref name=\"df-dt1964\" /><ref name=\"ber-storm\" /> At the end of the season, the two clubs with the fewest points in the final league standings, [[Akademisk Boldklub|Akademisk BK]] and [[Br\u00f8nsh\u00f8j Boldklub|Br\u00f8nsh\u00f8j BK]], were relegated to the [[1965 Danish 2nd Division]].<ref name=\"df-dt1964\" /> [[J\u00f8rgen Ravn]] of [[Kj\u00f8benhavns Boldklub|Kj\u00f8benhavns BK]] was the league's top scorer for the second time, scoring 21 goals, three more than second-placed team mate [[Finn M\u00f8ller]].<ref name=\"rsssf-1d1964\" />\n\n== Summary ==\n{{external media\n| float  = right\n| image1 = [http://web.archive.org/web/20200414011105/https://filweb.arkibas.dk/filer/visning/f32c0599ed63a001dcf52a08c7969ef3 The players of B 1909 at the award ceremony], crowned 1964 [[List of Danish football champions|Danish league champions]], following the away match against [[Kj\u00f8benhavns Boldklub|Kj\u00f8benhavns BK]] on 15 November 1964. [[Bruno Eliasen]] is holding the league trophy.\n}}\n\nB 1909 claimed the league title on the final matchday, 15 November, with a 1\u20130 away win at [[K\u00f8benhavns Idr\u00e6tspark]] in a top flight clash against another title contender [[Kj\u00f8benhavns Boldklub|Kj\u00f8benhavns BK]].<ref name=\"ber-storm\" /> The weather on that Sunday was cold, windy and raining, but the deciding match of season managed to attract a crowd of 43,400 spectators \u2014 it remains the official standing record attendance for a Danish league game.<ref name=\"ber-storm\" /><ref name=\"dbuk-ki\" /> Before the last round, both teams were leading the league table, each with 29 points, followed by Aarhus GF in third place with 27 points \u2014 B 1909 held a slightly better [[goal average]].<ref name=\"has-1d1964\" /> The interest for the game was fueled by the fact that the past [[List of Danish football champions|ten top-tier league seasons]] had been won by provincial teams, and that the game involved a [[Copenhagen]]-based team, which could reclaim the Danish league title \u2014 the first 41 editions of Danish national football championship had been won by a club from the capital.<ref name=\"ber-storm\" /> Despite the stadium being able to hold approximately 50,000 spectators at the time and no brewing unrest, the authorities decided the close the gates 15 minutes before [[Kick-off (association football)|kick-off]] due to fears of overcrowding.<ref name=\"ber-storm\" /> A good portion of freeists had more or less illegally obtained a spot at the stands inside the stadium, while several thousand people outside the stadium could not get access.<ref name=\"ber-storm\" /><ref name=\"b09-h3d\" />\n\nThe final match was won by B 1909 with a single goal netted by forward [[Mogens Haastrup]] in the 80th minute of play, following a pass from team mate [[John Danielsen]], where Haastrup dribbled and eluded Kj\u00f8benhavns BK goalkeeper Nils Jensen.<ref name=\"b09-h3d\" /> B 1909 goalkeeper [[Svend Aage Rask]], dressed in complete black, prevented several goal attempt from Kj\u00f8benhavns BK's forwards, including [[J\u00f8rgen Ravn]].<ref name=\"b09-h3d\" /> [[Hungarians|Hungarian]]-[[Swiss people|Swiss]] [[Carlos Pint\u00e9r]] was head coach for the [[Odense]]-based [[working class]] team in corporation with a match selection committee and had the following core players in the club's squad: goalkeeper [[Svend Aage Rask]], defenders [[Leif Hartwig]] and [[J\u00f8rgen Rask]], midfielders [[Arno Hansen]], [[Erling Nielsen (footballer)|Erling Nielsen]] and Per Jacobsen, and forwards [[Palle K\u00e4hler]], [[Walther Richter]], Mogens Haastrup, John Danielsen and [[Mogens Berg]].<ref name=\"b09-h3d\" /> Palle Hansen, Mogens Engstr\u00f8m and [[Bruno Eliasen]], who all appeared in the last game of the season, including J\u00f8rgen Petersen and Poul Erik Wiinberg, also played their part in the winning season.<ref name=\"b09-h3d\" /><ref name=\"fh-b09\" /><ref name=\"b09-mh\" />\n\n[[Boldklubben Frem|BK Frem]] and [[Boldklubben 1903|B 1903]] secured themselves another season in the top-flight division by winning their last games on 15 November 1964, 4\u20130 at home against [[Vejle Boldklub|Vejle BK]] and 3\u20131 away against [[Nyk\u00f8bing Falster Boldklub af 1901|B 1901]], respectively.<ref name=\"bkf-s1964\" /><ref name=\"frem125\" /><ref name=\"has-1d1964\" /> The decisive match for BK Frem took place at [[Valby Idr\u00e6tspark]] in front of an audience of 3,000 spectators compared to the club's other home matches in the season, that had all been played at K\u00f8benhavns Idr\u00e6tspark.<ref name=\"bkf-s1964\" /><ref name=\"frem125\" /> [[Akademisk Boldklub|Akademisk BK]], who was also part of the relegation battle, won their last match away against [[Boldklubben 1913|B 1913]], but ended up with just one point short in the final standings, so was relegated to the [[1965 Danish 2nd Division]] along with [[Br\u00f8nsh\u00f8j Boldklub|Br\u00f8nsh\u00f8j BK]].<ref name=\"has-1d1964\" />\n\n== Teams ==\n<!--{{See also |List of Danmarksturneringen clubs}}-->\nTwelve teams competed in the league \u2013 the top ten teams from the [[1963 Danish 1st Division|previous season]] and the two teams promoted from the [[1963 Danish 2nd Division|second-tier]]. The promoted teams were [[Boldklubben af 1893|B.93]], returning to the top flight after a four-year absence, and [[Boldklubben Frem|BK Frem]], returning after a three-year absence. They replaced [[Aalborg Boldspilklub|Aalborg BK]] and [[K\u00f8ge Boldklub|K\u00f8ge BK]], ending their top flight spells of one and three years respectively.\n\n=== Stadiums and locations ===\n{{location map+ |Denmark |float=right |width=550 |caption=Locations of the 1964 Danish 1st Division teams.|places=\n{{location map~ |Denmark |lat=55.702469 |long=12.572203 |label='''Copenhagen'''|mark=Black pog.svg|position=bottom}}\n{{location map~ |Denmark |lat=55.481985 |long=8.43941 |label=[[Esbjerg fB]]|position=bottom}}\n{{location map~ |Denmark |lat=54.771131 |long=11.877667 |label=[[Nyk\u00f8bing Falster Boldklub af 1901|B 1901]]|position=right}}\n{{location map~ |Denmark |lat=55.397771 |long=10.350055 |label='''Odense'''|mark=Black pog.svg|position=top}}\n{{location map~ |Denmark |lat=55.713814 |long=9.557161 |label=[[Vejle Boldklub|Vejle BK]]|position=top}}\n{{location map~ |Denmark |lat=56.131944 |long=10.196389 |label=[[Aarhus Gymnastikforening|Aarhus&nbsp;GF]]|position=right}}\n\n{{Location map~ |Denmark |mark=TransparentPlaceholder.png |marksize=1 |lat=57.5 |long=13 |label={{nowrap|'''Copenhagen teams'''}}\n{{nowrap|<br />[[Akademisk Boldklub|Akademisk BK]]<br />[[Boldklubben af 1893|B.93]]<br />[[Boldklubben 1903|B 1903]]<br />[[Br\u00f8nsh\u00f8j Boldklub|Br\u00f8nsh\u00f8j BK]]<br />[[Boldklubben Frem|BK Frem]]<br />[[Kj\u00f8benhavns Boldklub|Kj\u00f8benhavns BK]]}}\n{{nowrap|<br /><br />'''Odense teams'''}}\n{{nowrap|<br />[[Boldklubben 1909|B 1909]]<br />[[Boldklubben 1913|B 1913]]}}}}\n}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Club\n! Location\n! Stadium\n! Capacity\n! Ref\n|-\n| [[Akademisk Boldklub|Akademisk BK]]\n| \n| [[K\u00f8benhavns Idr\u00e6tspark]]\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|{{Nts|51,000}}\n| <ref name=\"dbuk-ki\" />\n|-\n| [[Aarhus Gymnastikforening|Aarhus GF]]\n| [[Aarhus]]\n| [[Aarhus Stadium]]\n| \n| \n|-\n| [[Boldklubben af 1893|B.93]]\n| [[\u00d8sterbro]], [[Copenhagen]]\n| [[K\u00f8benhavns Idr\u00e6tspark]]\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|{{Nts|51,000}}\n\n| <ref name=\"dbuk-ki\" />\n|-\n| [[Nyk\u00f8bing Falster Boldklub af 1901|B 1901]]\n| [[Nyk\u00f8bing Falster]]\n| \n| \n| \n|-\n| [[Boldklubben 1903|B 1903]]\n| \n| [[K\u00f8benhavns Idr\u00e6tspark]]\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|{{Nts|51,000}}\n\n| <ref name=\"dbuk-ki\" />\n|-\n| [[Boldklubben 1909|B 1909]]\n| [[Odense]]\n| [[Odense Stadium]]\n| \n| \n|-\n| [[Boldklubben 1913|B 1913]]\n| [[Odense]]\n| [[Odense Stadium]]\n| \n| \n|-\n| [[Br\u00f8nsh\u00f8j Boldklub|Br\u00f8nsh\u00f8j BK]]\n| \n| [[K\u00f8benhavns Idr\u00e6tspark]]\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|{{Nts|51,000}}\n\n| <ref name=\"dbuk-ki\" />\n|-\n| [[Esbjerg fB]]\n| [[Esbjerg]]\n| [[Esbjerg Stadium]]\n| \n| \n|-\n| [[Boldklubben Frem|BK Frem]]\n| [[Valby]], [[Copenhagen]]\n| [[K\u00f8benhavns Idr\u00e6tspark]] <small>(21 matches)</small><br />[[Valby Idr\u00e6tspark]] <small>(1 match)<!--15 November 1964 against Vejle BK--></small>\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|{{Nts|51,000}}<br />\u2014\n| <ref name=\"dbuk-ki\" /><ref name=\"bkf-s1964\" /><ref name=\"frem125\" />\n|-\n| [[Kj\u00f8benhavns Boldklub|Kj\u00f8benhavns BK]]\n| [[Frederiksberg]]\n| [[K\u00f8benhavns Idr\u00e6tspark]]\n|style=\"text-align:center\"|{{Nts|51,000}}\n\n| <ref name=\"dbuk-ki\" />\n|-\n| [[Vejle Boldklub|Vejle BK]]\n| [[Vejle]]\n| [[Vejle Athletic Stadium]]\n| \n| \n|}\n\n=== Personnel ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Team\n! Head coach\n! Captain\n! Ref\n|-\n| [[Akademisk Boldklub|Akademisk BK]]\n| {{flagicon|DEN}} [[Ivan Jessen]]<!--Ivan Jessen-Petersen-->\n| \n| <ref name=\"df1964teams\" />\n|-\n| [[Aarhus Gymnastikforening|Aarhus GF]]\n| {{flagicon|HUN}} [[G\u00e9za Toldi]]\n| \n| <ref name=\"df1964teams\" />\n|-\n| [[Boldklubben af 1893|B.93]]\n| {{flagicon|DEN}} [[Knud Petersen (footballer)|Knud Petersen]]\n| \n| <ref name=\"df1964teams\" />\n|-\n| [[Nyk\u00f8bing Falster Boldklub af 1901|B 1901]]\n| {{flagicon|DEN}} [[Kurt \"Nikkelaj\" Nielsen]]\n| \n| <ref name=\"df1964teams\" />\n|-\n| [[Boldklubben 1903|B 1903]]\n| {{flagicon|DEN}} [[Simon Mathiesen]]\n| \n| <ref name=\"df1964teams\" />\n|-\n| [[Boldklubben 1909|B 1909]]\n| {{flagicon|HUN}} {{sortname|Carlos|Pint\u00e9r}}\n| {{flagicon|DEN}} [[Erling Nielsen (footballer)|Erling Nielsen]] <small>(18 caps)</small><br />{{flagicon|DEN}} [[Bruno Eliasen]] <small>(4 caps)</small>\n| <ref name=\"b09-mh\" /><ref name=\"df1964teams\" />\n|-\n| [[Boldklubben 1913|B 1913]]\n| {{flagicon|DEN}} [[Jack Johnson (footballer, born 1924)|Jack Johnson]]<!--born Jack Johnsen-->\n| \n| <ref name=\"df1964teams\" />\n|-\n| [[Br\u00f8nsh\u00f8j Boldklub|Br\u00f8nsh\u00f8j BK]]\n| {{flagicon|DEN}} [[J\u00f8rn Larsen (footballer)|J\u00f8rn Larsen]]\n| \n| <ref name=\"df1964teams\" />\n|-\n| [[Esbjerg fB]]\n| {{flagicon|DEN}} {{sortname|Arne|S\u00f8rensen}}\n| {{flagicon|DEN}} {{sortname|Jens J\u00f8rgen|Hansen}}\n| <ref name=\"efbh-t\" /><ref name=\"df1964teams\" />\n|-\n| [[Boldklubben Frem|BK Frem]]\n| {{flagicon|DEN}} [[Erling S\u00f8rensen]]\n| {{flagicon|DEN}} [[Birger Larsen (footballer)|Birger Larsen]]\n| <ref name=\"df1964teams\" />\n|-\n| [[Kj\u00f8benhavns Boldklub|Kj\u00f8benhavns BK]]\n| \n| \n| \n|-\n| [[Vejle Boldklub|Vejle BK]]\n| {{flagicon|AUT}} [[Ernst Netuka]]\n| \n| <ref name=\"df1964teams\" />\n|}\n\n== League table ==\nEvery team played two games against the other teams, at home and away, totaling 22 games each. Teams received two points for a win and one point for a draw. If two or more teams were tied on points, places were determined by [[goal average]]. The team with the most points were crowned winners of the league, while the two teams with the fewest points would be relegated to the [[1965 Danish 2nd Division]].\n\n{{#invoke:Sports table|main|style=football\n|source=<ref name=\"df-dt1964\" /><ref name=\"df3\" /><ref name=\"rsssf-1d1964\" />\n|use_goal_ratio=yes\n|winpoints=2\n\n<!--Update team positions here-->\n|team1=B09 |team2=AGF |team3=KBK |team4=EFB |team5=VBK |team6=B13 |team7=B01 |team8=B93 |team9=BKF |team10=B03 |team11=ABK |team12=BBK\n\n<!--Update team qualifications here (defined below)-->\n|result1=EC |result4=ECWC |result10=ICFC |result11=REL |result12=REL\n\n<!--Update team results here and then (if needed) positions above. Dont forget to update the date (update parameter)-->\n|update=complete\n|win_B09=14 |draw_B09=3 |loss_B09=5  |gf_B09=53 |ga_B09=33\n|win_AGF=